<span id="freeTextContainer9939395853976943693">Bereft is a fascinating novel for fans of the gothic. There is a crime, but the interest in this story is nothing to do with whodunnit. That’s obvious from early on; it’s the story of a man coming-to-terms with his own life that makes it such a compelling tale. The characterisation is memorable, and Womersley’s prose and imagery is so vivid that I found myself stopping to savour it often. My reading journal is full of superb quotations and images that I copied out by hand as examples of a writer</span>
  <span id="freeText9939395853976943693" style="display:none">Bereft is a fascinating novel for fans of the gothic. There is a crime, but the interest in this story is nothing to do with whodunnit. That’s obvious from early on; it’s the story of a man coming-to-terms with his own life that makes it such a compelling tale. The characterisation is memorable, and Womersley’s prose and imagery is so vivid that I found myself stopping to savour it often. My reading journal is full of superb quotations and images that I copied out by hand as examples of a writer in full control of his craft.<br /><br />To read the rest of my review please visit <a target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow" href="http://anzlitlovers.wordpress.com/2011/01/21/bereft-by-chris-womersley/">http://anzlitlovers.wordpress.com/201...</a></span>
